[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Boy oh boy. I am so excited to show you this.&nbsp; The scientists behind this new research paper&nbsp;&nbsp; reached out to me and I got to say, I&nbsp; am speechless. Look at this. What you&nbsp;&nbsp; are seeing is not reality. This is a computer&nbsp; simulation. I mean, what? But that is nothing&nbsp;&nbsp; compared to what I found out about this work. It&nbsp; improves on what I think is one of the best papers&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ever written, Wavelet Turbulence. You see, a low&nbsp; resolution simulation can be computed quickly,&nbsp;&nbsp; but a high resolution, really detailed one can&nbsp; take forever. So Wavelet Turbulence was a way&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of taking a coarse simulation quickly, and then&nbsp; recreating it as this breathtaking quality. One of&nbsp;&nbsp; the best papers ever written I think. Yes, I keep&nbsp; saying that. It also won a technical Oscar award.'

[00:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But it had many limitations, for&nbsp; instance, it simulated the smoke&nbsp;&nbsp; or water within a fixed box of cells.&nbsp; Outside the box, nothing happens. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can make the box huge to cover a large&nbsp; scene, but the memory and compute cost explode,&nbsp;&nbsp; making it extremely inefficient. So if you have a&nbsp; huge area, grids are suddenly not too appealing.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now particle-based techniques solve this because&nbsp; these are particles after all, and they can travel&nbsp;&nbsp; wherever they please. They are not confined to&nbsp; a grid. Fantastic. Okay, so are we done here?'

[01:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Well, not quite. You see, particles are also&nbsp; inefficient in large scales. To be able to&nbsp;&nbsp; compute pressure, density, surface tension, and&nbsp; all the goodies you need for a proper simulation,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these particles need to ask their neighbors&nbsp; for some information. For instance, to know&nbsp;&nbsp; how dense the fluid is around them, each particle&nbsp; has to search for all nearby particles within a&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'certain radius. They must repeat this neighbor&nbsp; search every time step. It is the same with us,&nbsp;&nbsp; if you have a couple neighbors, not a problem,&nbsp; just ask for their signature for a petition,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'not a problem, right? Just pop in there, 2 houses&nbsp; and we are done. However, now, Fellow Scholars,&nbsp;&nbsp; imagine that you have billions and billions of&nbsp; neighbors. That is of course, impossible right?'

[02:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, believe it or not, computer graphics&nbsp; researchers are beyond amazing, and they&nbsp;&nbsp; solved this problem too by building a city hall in&nbsp; the middle of the neighborhood - this is the grid.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Welcome back, little grid! So, instead&nbsp; of asking every neighbor one by one,&nbsp;&nbsp; all neighbors, that is, particles just send their&nbsp; signatures to the city hall, that is the grid,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and the city hall does one big calculation&nbsp; for everyone. These billions of particles&nbsp;&nbsp; instead of interacting with each other, they&nbsp; interact with the central government. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'unlike real government centers,&nbsp; this is actually, really efficient. And then, it sends the result back to each&nbsp; house. This we call grid-to-particle transfer. And the city hall technique is called FLIP,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fluid implicit particle, and it is a hybrid&nbsp; method. A marriage of particles and grids. Okay, so what is the problem? Why&nbsp; do we need this new technique? Well, FLIP cannot easily combine&nbsp; air and water interaction,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'so no spray particles for us. It&nbsp; is possible, but not easy. Also,&nbsp;&nbsp; cinematic simulations need billions of particles&nbsp; and huge grids. This is still too costly. So, this new technique promises the&nbsp; impossible. High-quality simulations,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with water spray particles, all the goodies that&nbsp; I am yearning for. But quickly. I don’t believe&nbsp;&nbsp; any of it, so now, hold on to your papers&nbsp; Fellow Scholars and let’s have a look…oh&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'my goodness. Do you see how crisp this is? This&nbsp; is so good, I am getting goosebumps here. Wow.&nbsp;&nbsp; With this incredible detail, yes, you can get&nbsp; your spray particles but that’s nothing man,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can even simulate a huge asteroid impact,&nbsp; a dam break scene, whatever you wish. Goodness! Is this reality? Am I dreaming? How is&nbsp; this even possible? Dear Fellow Scholars,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this is Two Minute Papers with Dr.&nbsp; Károly Zsolnai-Fehér. Dr. Carroll. Well, it does three things&nbsp; really well to accomplish that. First, previous techniques were able to do&nbsp; adaptive particles. More particles where the&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'real action happens, fewer where there is not much&nbsp; going on. That is, more computation for particles&nbsp;&nbsp; wherever needed, and that is excellent. This one&nbsp; was written by Ryoichi Ando, and when I visited&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'them a few years ago, he did not come to my talk&nbsp; because he was busy with this paper. I am very&nbsp;&nbsp; sad. But you know what sir, you are officially&nbsp; forgiven. This work is just too good, and way&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more important than my stupid talk. And he’s&nbsp; been up to amazing works ever since. And look,&nbsp;&nbsp; he is unaffiliated. This is usually when you get&nbsp; a nice little offer from NVIDIA, but maybe Jensen&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'doesn’t know about him yet. And I kinda wanna do&nbsp; an episode on most of these papers. Loving it. Okay, but all this was adaptive particles only.&nbsp; We need to combine it with adaptive grids. And,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'yes, one! The new research work finally&nbsp; uses adaptive grids and adaptive particles.&nbsp;&nbsp; Finally! This means we only spend computing&nbsp; power where the action is – like putting&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'streetlights only where people actually walk&nbsp; instead of lighting up the entire street. Two - it uses a phase field to naturally&nbsp; separate air and water. No more manually&nbsp;&nbsp; tracing the shoreline! It’s like having a smart&nbsp; drone that automatically draws the border between&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'land and sea every frame so you always know&nbsp; where the splash ends and the air begins. And three - it has a fast adaptive Poisson&nbsp; solver that keeps the pressure computation&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from eating all the runtime. Yum yum yum.&nbsp; Think of it as a super-efficient city hall&nbsp;&nbsp; clerk who processes everyone’s paperwork in&nbsp; parallel instead of letting the line go around&nbsp;&nbsp; the block. Ah man, we are back talking&nbsp; about the government again. Goodness.'

[06:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay, so an absolutely brilliant&nbsp; piece of research, and once again,&nbsp;&nbsp; it is breaking my heart because almost nobody&nbsp; is talking about it. Nobody else does that that&nbsp;&nbsp; I know of. These papers are like endangered&nbsp; species. I\'m trying to save them. Before we&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'look at how long we have to wait for such&nbsp; a simulation, and how close or not close it&nbsp;&nbsp; can get to reality in the toughest test, please&nbsp; like, subscribe, and leave a really kind comment&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to help these endangered species, and to help&nbsp; you get more videos like this in the future. It runs so fast that even billion-particle, yes,&nbsp; billion particle cinematic-resolution simulations&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'finish on a single workstation in minutes&nbsp; per frame. So something that was previously&nbsp;&nbsp; close to impossible is now possible within&nbsp; just a few hours. What a time to be alive!'

[07:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
